<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="78" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,438,1867]" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1662,1687]" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">Remarks.</emphasis>
The male of this new species is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authority="Zavattari" authorityName="Zavattari" box="[913,1264,1662,1687]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Hemutilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hoozana">
<emphasis box="[913,1131,1662,1686]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">Hemutilla hoozana</emphasis>
(Zavattari)
</taxonomicName>
, but differs by having the mandible basally strongly widened beneath, acute (slightly rounded in 
<taxonomicName box="[1081,1211,1699,1723]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Hemutilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hoozana">
<emphasis box="[1081,1211,1699,1723]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">H. hoozana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); the lateral section of the clypeus not concave, granulate (concave, coarsely punctate in 
<taxonomicName box="[918,1047,1734,1758]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Hemutilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hoozana">
<emphasis box="[918,1047,1734,1758]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">H. hoozana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); the volsellar cuspis mesally with strong, long setae (with much shorter setae in 
<taxonomicName box="[666,796,1771,1795]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Hemutilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hoozana">
<emphasis box="[666,796,1771,1795]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">H. hoozana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="78" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,438,1867]" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1806,1831]" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is a Latin adjective meaning &quot;granulose&quot;, with reference to the sculpture of the lateral section of the clypeus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
